Joël-Peter Witkin – The Art and the Manner (L’art et la Manière) @ Palais Du Roi de Rome in Rambouillet, France

Joël-Peter Witkin was born in New York in 1939 to a Jewish father of Russian origin and a practicing Catholic mother of Italian origin.  As a child, he witnesses a car accident during which a little girl is decapitated.  This experience, which marked him for life, gave him a certain taste for the morbid and strange, sometimes even "monstrous" images.  But above all, Witkin is an immensely cultured artist, nourished by the masterpieces of Western art.  The techniques he uses are of a great variety and each of his photographs has been the subject of long reflection and patient elaboration.  It has notably been exhibited at the MOMA in New York and at the National Library of France.  He now lives in New Mexico.

Until 31 December 2022

The exhibition of photographer Joel-Peter Witkin is not to the taste of the town hall of Rambouillet

After receiving several protest emails deeming his work "blasphemous", the city of Yvelines chose to withdraw the displays and arrows to the presentation of the American artist, at the palace of the King of Rome.

We barely received a few protest emails, and that was enough to push back the town hall of Rambouillet!” Baudoin Lebon 's incomprehension can be heard on the other end of the line. The gallery owner, who has exhibited photographer Joel-Peter Witkin for more than forty years, must now manage what he considers to be censorship from the town hall of Rambouillet, who has exhibited his works at the palace of the King of Rome for October 29.

The situation surprises the photographer who is known to be a devout Catholic himself. “None of my exhibitions has ever provoked protest or led to any form of censorship, not even in China ,” stings the artist in aninterview with Télérama . Irony of fate: with the controversy, the exhibition benefits from a significant Streisand effect. "Since we tried to censor it, the photographs attract twice as many people ", welcomes Baudoin Lebon. Joel-Peter Witkin. The art and the way is still visible at the Palace of the King of Rome, in Rambouillet until December 31.

Joel-Peter Witkin on the Beauty in the Grotesque by @blind.magazine

With an exhibition at Badouin Lebon in Paris, another one at Bruce Silverstein in New York, and work on view at the Louvre, Witkin speaks about his creative process.

In Joel-Peter Witkin’s world, death is not to be feared. Instead, there is beauty in the macabre, and some humor there too, as evidenced from his lifelong career creating photographs that evoke a range of reactions from outrage to wonder. With still lifes featuring dismembered body parts, and portraits of transsexual people posed in classical art forms, Witkin’s brand of subversiveness has established him as one of the most important contemporary photographers today. 
An exhibition at galerie baudoin lebon, in Paris, “Joel-Peter Witkin: The Untold Life of the Photograph” explores Witkin’s creative process: encaustic photography, props from his immaculately staged tableaus, and contact sheets with scribbled handwriting all plunge the viewer into Witkin’s world, by turns dark and paradisiacal. 

One of Witkin’s most famous images, Harvest, is on view at the Musée du Louvre as a part of their “Les Choses: Une histoire de la nature morte” exhibition. A face is strung across a gathering of branches and leaves, with the same whimsy as Arcimboldo’s Vertumnus, a 16th century painting depicting a man made entirely out of vegetables and flowers. But where Vertumnus was made for humorous effect, there’s a beauty and tranquility in Harvest.

Joel-Peter Witkin, “Siamese Twins” Los Angeles, 1988

Quote from a recent lecture at UTEP:

“I was made aware of the Siamese twins, Yvonne and Yvette, from a LA Times newspaper article about the sisters attending college. Their mother was very religious; she had sheltered them because she was afraid that people would be mean to them. When the twins were in their thirties their mother died. / Now they were able to make their own decisions. /
They went to college. They had separate interests, but of course they had to sit through each other’s classes.They wanted to date.They were making up for lost time and agreed to be photographed. /
Each twin had her own individual brain. There had been a good chance that they could have been successfully separated but their mother had not wanted them to go through the surgery. When I asked if given the opportunity would they want to be separated now. Both simultaneously said, NEVER! /
They existed together. In conversation, each could finish the others sentences and thoughts. Sometimes they spoke in unison sounding like a soft echo. During the shoot the twins very distinct personalities became apparent. Yvette on the left was frightened of the bird so she got to hold the flowers while Yvonne was thrilled to hold the bird. /
Being in the twins presence was like being given a gift. They were so sweet and kind and were embracing life making up for lost time. The air was electric. /
Five years after the photograph was taken/ they died together at the age of 43.”

The baudoin lebon Gallery pays tribute to the Texbraun Gallery, with the complicity of Jonas Tebib. Group show opening tonight, Wednesday, December 6th from 6 pm-9 pm. 

Images included:

The Kiss (Le Braiser), New Mexico, 1982
Harvest (Encaustic Version), Philadelphia, 1984
Lisa Lyon as Hercules, NYC, 1983
Lisa Lyon as the Amnavyssos Kouros, NYC, 1983

François Braunschweig and Hugues Autexier, better known as Texbraun, started as booksellers before establishing themselves at the Flea Market and founding their gallery on Mazarine Street. Under their passionate direction, the Texbraun Gallery exhibited 19th-century photographers while promoting contemporary artists such as Robert Mapplethorpe, Pierre et Gilles, Joel-Peter Witkin, and Bettina Rheims.
 
The Texbraun Gallery played a crucial role in establishing photography's recognition in France, contributing to the dynamic evolution of the photography market. It closed its doors in 1986, leaving an indelible legacy in French photography history.
